"Hansen J., Sato M.","Greenhouse gas growth rates",2004,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","101","46",,"16109","16114",,,10.1073/pnas.0406982101,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-9244221615&partnerID=40&md5=b5e1017ee4a19c3e50743214f9a09d32","Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Columbia University Earth Institute, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States","Hansen, J., Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Columbia University Earth Institute, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Sato, M., Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Columbia University Earth Institute, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States","We posit that feasible reversal of the growth of atmospheric CH4 and other trace gases would provide a vital contribution toward averting dangerous anthropogenic interference with global climate. Such trace gas reductions may allow stabilization of atmospheric CO2 at an achievable level of anthropogenic CO2 emissions, even if the added global warming constituting dangerous anthropogenic interference is as small as 1°C. A 1°C limit on global warming, with canonical climate sensitivity, requires peak CO2 ≈ 440 ppm if further non-CO2 forcing is +0.5 W/m2, but peak CO2 ≈ 520 ppm if further non-CO2 forcing is -0.5 W/m2. The practical result is that a decline of non-CO2 forcings allows climate forcing to be stabilized with a significantly higher transient level of CO2 emissions. Increased ""natural"" emissions of CO2, N 2O, and CH4 are expected in response to global warming. These emissions, an indirect effect of all climate forcings, are small compared with human-made climate forcing and occur on a time scale of a few centuries, but they tend to aggravate the task of stabilizing atmospheric composition.","Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Fossil fuels; Methane","carbon dioxide; methane; nitrous oxide; trace element; air pollution control; article; atmospheric dispersion; controlled study; global climate; greenhouse effect; greenhouse gas; growth rate; nitrous oxide emission; priority journal",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; methane, 74-82-8; nitrous oxide, 10024-97-2",,,,"Hansen, J., Ruedy, R., Sato, M., Imhoff, M., Lawrence, W., Easterling, D., Peterson, T., Karl, T., (2001) J. Geophys. Res., 106, pp. 23947-23963; Jones, P.D., Moberg, A., (2003) J. Climate, 16, pp. 206-223; Houghton, J.T., Ding, Y., Griggs, D.J., Noguer, M., Van Der Linden, P.J., Dai, X., Maskell, K., Johnson, C.A., (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis: Contributions of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, U.K; Hansen, J., Sato, M., Ruedy, R., (1997) J. Geophys. Res., 102, pp. 6831-6864; Ramaswamy, V., (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis: Contributions of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 349-416. , eds. Houghton J. T., Ding, Y., Griggs, D. J., Noguer, M., van der Linden, P. J., Dai, X., Maskell, K. & Johnson, C. A. (Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, U.K.); Ramanathan, V., Crutzen, P.J., Kiehl, J.T., Rosenfeld, D., (2001) Science, 294, pp. 2119-2124; Hansen, J., Lacis, A., Ruedy, R., Sato, M., Wilson, H., (1993) Natl. Geogr. Res. Explor., 9, pp. 142-158; Hansen, J., Nazarenko, L., (2004) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 101, pp. 423-428; Hansen, J., Lacis, A., Rind, D., Russell, G., Stone, P., Fung, I., Ruedy, R., Lerner, J., (1984) Geophys. Monogr., 29, pp. 130-163; Levitus, S., Antonov, J.I., Boyer, T.P., Stephens, C., (2000) Science, 287, pp. 2225-2229; Hansen, J., (2004) Sci. Am., 290 (3), pp. 68-77; O'Neill, B.C., Oppenheimer, M., (2002) Science, 296, pp. 1971-1972; Hansen, J.E., Sato, M., Ruedy, R., Lacis, A., Oinas, V., (2000) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 97, pp. 9875-988